<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">22492681</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2012</Year><Month>09</Month><Day>04</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2024</Year><Month>08</Month><Day>08</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">2047-6310</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>7</Volume><Issue>3</Issue><PubDate><Year>2012</Year><Month>Jun</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Pediatric obesity</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Pediatr Obes</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Improving physical self-perception in adolescent boys from disadvantaged schools: psychological outcomes from the Physical Activity Leaders randomized controlled trial.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>e27</StartPage><EndPage>e32</EndPage><MedlinePgn>e27-32</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1111/j.2047-6310.2012.00050.x</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVES" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">To evaluate the effect of a school-based obesity prevention programme on physical self-perception and key physical-activity related cognitions in adolescent boys from disadvantaged secondary schools. A secondary objective was to determine if any psychological changes were associated with improved weight status.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Participants (n&#x2009;=&#x2009;100, age&#x2009;=&#x2009;14.3[0.6]) were randomized to the PALS (Physical Activity Leaders) intervention (n&#x2009;=&#x2009;50) or a control group (n&#x2009;=&#x2009;50) and assessed at baseline, 3- and 6-month follow up. Measures included BMI, BMI z-score and % body fat (bioelectrical impedance analysis). Students also completed the Children's Physical Self-Perception Profile and a physical activity-related cognitions questionnaire. The findings include secondary data analyses.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Relative to the controls, the PALS group significantly increased their physical self worth (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;.01), perceived physical condition (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;.02), resistance training self efficacy (p&#x2009;&lt;&#x2009;.001) and their use of physical activity behavioural strategies (p&#x2009;=&#x2009;.02).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">A school-based obesity prevention programme that targeted leadership skills improved psychological health in the physical domain in adolescent boys from disadvantaged schools.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2012 The Authors. Pediatric Obesity &#xa9; 2012 International Association for the Study of Obesity.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Morgan</LastName><ForeName>P J</ForeName><Initials>PJ</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Faculty of Education &amp; Arts, University of Newcastle, Callaghan, NSW, Australia. philip.morgan@newcastle.edu.au</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Saunders</LastName><ForeName>K L</ForeName><Initials>KL</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Lubans</LastName><ForeName>D R</ForeName><Initials>DR</Initials></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016449">Randomized Controlled Trial</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D013485">Research Support, Non-U.S. Gov't</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2012</Year><Month>04</Month><Day>10</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>England</Country><MedlineTA>Pediatr Obes</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>101572033</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>2047-6302</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><MeshHeadingList><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D050154" MajorTopicYN="N">Adiposity</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading